SIMPLE: interjection
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Interjection
<hw>In`ter*jec"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>interjectio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>interjection</ets>. See
<er>Interject</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of interjecting or throwing between; also,
that which is interjected.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>interjection</qex> of laughing.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Gram.)</fld> <def>A word or form of speech thrown
in to express emotion or feeling, as <xex>O</xex>! <xex>Alas</xex>!
<xex>Ha ha</xex>! <xex>Begone</xex>! etc. Compare
<er>Exclamation</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An <qex>interjection</qex> implies a meaning which it would
require a whole grammatical sentence to expound, and it may be regarded
as the rudiment of such a sentence. But it is a confusion of thought to
rank it among the parts of speech.</q> <rj><qau>Earle.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How now! <qex>interjections</qex>? Why, then, some be of laughing,
as, ah, ha, he!</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Interjectional</ent>⟦br⟧
